===============================================================================
 N500 MOMENTUM SCORING — EXECUTION GUIDE
===============================================================================

OVERVIEW
--------
Two Python scripts compute momentum scores for NSE Nifty 500 stocks and
output a ranked Excel workbook.

  momentum_lib.py   Library of reusable scoring functions (do not run directly)
  Sharpe.py         Main script — loads data, calls the library, writes output


REQUIRED FILES (all in the same folder)
----------------------------------------
  momentum_lib.py       (library — must be present for Sharpe.py to work)
  Sharpe.py             (main script)
  n500.xlsx             (input price data — see format notes below)


DEPENDENCIES
------------
Install once using pip:

  pip install pandas numpy openpyxl scipy

Python version: 3.9 or higher recommended.


INPUT FILE FORMAT  (n500.xlsx)
-------------------------------
Sheet name  : DATA
Row 1       : Header row
  - Column 1        : TICKER  (text label e.g. "ASHOKLEY", "NIFTY500")
  - Column 2        : CLOSE   (latest close price — informational)
  - Column 3        : 52WK HIGH
  - Columns 4+      : Daily close prices, one column per trading date
                      Column header must be a date value (Excel date format)

Special rows:
  - NIFTY500        : Must be present — used as the market benchmark for
                      residual momentum. It is automatically separated from
                      the stock universe before scoring.

Price data rules:
  - Missing / zero prices are treated as NaN and excluded from calculations
  - Stocks need at least 90% data coverage for a given window to receive a score
  - Duplicate tickers: if a ticker appears more than once, only the FIRST
    occurrence is used. Remove duplicates from the file before running.


HOW TO RUN
----------
Step 1.  Place all three files in the same folder:
           momentum_lib.py
           Sharpe.py
           n500.xlsx  (or any xlsx with the correct DATA sheet format)

Step 2.  Open a terminal / command prompt and navigate to that folder.

Step 3.  Run the script:

           python Sharpe.py                        # uses n500.xlsx by default
           python Sharpe.py path/to/myfile.xlsx    # explicit path

Step 4.  The script prints progress and top-20 results to the console.

Step 5.  Output file is written to the same folder as Sharpe.py:
           n500_rankings.xlsx


WHAT THE SCRIPT COMPUTES (in order)
-------------------------------------
1. SHARPE RATIOS
   Windows : 1M (21d), 3M (63d), 6M (126d), 9M (189d), 12M (252d)
   Method  : Annualised Sharpe = mean(excess log-returns) / std * sqrt(252)
             Excess = log-return minus daily risk-free rate (7% / 252)
   Output  : S_1M, S_3M, S_6M, S_9M, S_12M

2. SHARPE Z-SCORES
   Each window is Z-scored cross-sectionally (mean=0, std=1 across all stocks)
   Output  : Z_1M, Z_3M, Z_6M, Z_9M, Z_12M

3. COMPOSITE SCORES (derived from Z-scores)
   SHARPE_ALL  = mean(Z_12M, Z_9M, Z_6M, Z_3M)  — 4-window equal-weighted
   SHARPE_3    = mean(Z_12M, Z_6M, Z_3M)         — 3-window (excludes 9M, 1M)
   SHARPE_ST   = mean(Z_1M, Z_3M, Z_6M)          — short-term (1-6 months)
   SHARPE_LT   = mean(Z_9M, Z_12M)               — long-term  (9-12 months)
   MOM_ACCEL   = Z(SHARPE_ST - SHARPE_LT)        — acceleration: positive =
                                                    momentum building recently

4. CLENOW SCORES  (windows: 3M, 6M, 9M, 12M only — not 1M)
   Method  : Fit log(price) = a + b*t over each window
             Raw Clenow = annualised slope * R²
             High score = strong uptrend with clean fit
   Z-scored cross-sectionally per window → CLENOW_Z composite

5. 52-WEEK HIGH FILTER
   PCT_FROM_52H = (last price / 52-week high - 1) * 100
   Eligibility  : PCT_FROM_52H >= -25  (stock must be within 25% of its high)
   Stocks outside this range receive no RANK but all scores are still computed

6. RESIDUAL MOMENTUM  (windows: 3M, 6M, 9M, 12M only — not 1M)
   Method  : For each window, regress stock log-returns on NIFTY500 log-returns
             using OLS. Compute Sharpe ratio on the residuals.
             High score = strong return not explained by market movement
   Z-scored cross-sectionally per window → RES_MOM composite

7. MARKET REGIME  (informational — does not affect ranking)
   BUY             : Last NIFTY500 price > EMA(50) AND EMA(21) > EMA(63)
   NOT BUY         : Either condition fails
   Shown in console output and Excel title row

8. RANKING
   Ranked by SHARPE_ALL (COMPOSITE) descending, eligible stocks only
   Ties broken by "first" method (order of appearance in data)


OUTPUT FILE  (n500_rankings.xlsx)
-----------------------------------
Sheet: TOP20
  Columns : RNK, TICKER, SHARPE_ALL, RES_MOM, MOM_ACCEL,
            SHARPE_3, SHARPE_ST, SHARPE_LT, 1M%, 3M%, 12M%
  Rows    : Top 20 ranked stocks (eligible only)

Sheet: CALCS
  All stocks, 33 columns:
  RANK, TICKER,
  S_12M, S_9M, S_6M, S_3M, S_1M,           (raw Sharpe per window)
  Z_12M, Z_9M, Z_6M, Z_3M, Z_1M,           (Sharpe Z-scores)
  SHARPE_ALL, SHARPE_ST, SHARPE_LT,
  SHARPE_3, MOM_ACCEL,
  RS_12M/9M/6M/3M,                          (residual Sharpe per window)
  RZ_12M/9M/6M/3M, RES_MOM,                (residual Z-scores + composite)
  1M%, 3M%, 12M%,                           (price returns)
  52H%                                      (% from 52-week high, green if >= -25)


USING momentum_lib.py IN YOUR OWN SCRIPT
-----------------------------------------
The library functions can be imported and called independently:

  import momentum_lib as ml

  prices_df, nifty_series, tickers, dates = ml.load_prices("n500.xlsx")

  sharpe_df, z_df = ml.compute_sharpe(
      prices_df, tickers,
      windows={"12M": 252, "3M": 63},
      rfr_daily=0.07/252,
      trading_days=252
  )


  resmom_df, rs_z_df = ml.compute_residual_momentum(
      prices_df, tickers, nifty_series,
      windows={"12M": 252, "3M": 63},
      trading_days=252
  )

  ret_df    = ml.compute_returns(prices_df, tickers)
  pct_52h   = ml.compute_pct_from_52h(prices_df, tickers)
  regime    = ml.compute_market_regime(nifty_series)


CONFIG PARAMETERS (top of Sharpe.py)
--------------------------------------
  RFR_ANNUAL    = 0.07     Risk-free rate (7% p.a. — change to match T-bill)
  TRADING_DAYS  = 252      Trading days per year (standard NSE assumption)
  TOP_N         = 20       Number of stocks to show in TOP20 sheet + console
  WINDOWS       = {...}    Windows for Residual Momentum
  SHARPE_WINDOWS= {...}    Windows for Sharpe (includes 1M)
  OUTPUT_FILE   = "n500_rankings.xlsx"   Change to rename the output


TYPICAL RUNTIME
---------------
  ~30-60 seconds on a standard laptop for 502 stocks
  Residual Momentum (OLS per stock per window) is the most compute-intensive step


TROUBLESHOOTING
---------------
  ModuleNotFoundError: momentum_lib     → Sharpe.py and momentum_lib.py must
                                          be in the same directory
  KeyError: 'NIFTY500'                  → DATA sheet must contain a NIFTY500 row
  KeyError: 'DATA'                      → Check xlsx sheet is named exactly DATA
  All scores NaN for a stock            → Stock has fewer than 90% valid prices
                                          for the shortest window required
  Duplicate index error                 → Remove duplicate tickers from the
                                          input file before running

